}

4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elemen:
{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.4. The GetResponse-PDU": [
        {
            "Original": "The form of the GetResponse-PDU is identical to that of the GetRequest-PDU except for the indication of the PDU type.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the ASN.1 language: GetResponse-PDU ::= [2] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { request-id RequestID, error-status ErrorStatus, error-index ErrorIndex, variable-bindings VarBindList } The GetResponse-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only upon receipt of the GetRequest-PDU, GetNextRequest-PDU, or SetRequest-PDU, as described elsewhere in this document.",
            "Adjusted": "In the ASN.1 language, GetResponse-PDU is defined as [2] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE containing request-id RequestID, error-status ErrorStatus, error-index ErrorIndex, and variable-bindings VarBindList. The GetResponse-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only upon receipt of the GetRequest-PDU, GetNextRequest-PDU, or SetRequest-PDU, as described elsewhere in this document."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of the GetResponse-PDU, the receiving protocol entity presents its contents to its SNMP application entity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU -> 4.1.6.1. The coldStart Trap": [
        {
            "Original": "A coldStart(0) trap signifies that the sending protocol entity is reinitializing itself such that the agent's configuration or the protocol entity implementation may be altered.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU -> 4.1.6.2. The warmStart Trap": [
        {
            "Original": "A warmStart(1) trap signifies that the sending protocol entity is reinitializing itself such that neither the agent configuration nor the protocol entity implementation is altered.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Introduction:
{
    "2. Introduction": [
        {
            "Original": "As reported inRFC 1052, IAB Recommendations for the Development of Internet Network Management Standards [1], a two-prong strategy for network management of TCP/IP-based internets was undertaken.",
            "Adjusted": "As reported in RFC 1052, IAB Recommendations for the Development of Internet Network Management Standards [1], a two-prong strategy for network management of TCP/IP-based internets was undertaken."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the short-term, the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) was to be used to manage nodes in the Internet community.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the long-term, the use of the OSI network management framework was to be examined.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Two documents were produced to define the management information: RFC 1065, which defined the Structure of Management Information (SMI) [2], and RFC 1066, which defined the Management Information Base (MIB) [3].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Both of these documents were designed so as to be compatible with both the SNMP and the OSI network management framework.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This strategy was quite successful in the short-term: Internet-based network management technology was fielded, by both the research and commercial communities, within a few months.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As a result of this, portions of the Internet community became network manageable in a timely fashion.",
            "Adjusted": "As a result of this strategy, portions of the Internet community became network manageable in a timely fashion."
        },
        {
            "Original": "As reported in RFC 1109, Report of the Second Ad Hoc Network Management Review Group [4], the requirements of the SNMP and the OSI network management frameworks were more different than anticipated.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As such, the requirement for compatibility between the SMI/MIB and both frameworks was suspended.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This action permitted the operational network management framework, the SNMP, to respond to new operational needs in the Internet community by producing documents defining new MIB items.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The IAB has designated the SNMP, SMI, and the initial Internet MIB to be full \"Standard Protocols\" with \"Recommended\" status.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "By this action, the IAB recommends that all IP and TCP implementations be network manageable and that the implementations that are network manageable are expected to adopt and implement the SMI, MIB, and SNMP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As such, the current network management framework for TCP/IP- based internets consists of: Structure and Identification of Management Information for TCP/IP-based Internets, which describes how managed objects contained in the MIB are defined as set forth in RFC 1155 [5]; Management Information Base for Network Management of TCP/IP- based Internets, which describes the managed objects contained in the MIB as set forth in RFC 1156 [6]; and, the Simple Network Management Protocol, which defines the protocol used to manage these objects, as set forth in this memo.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As reported in RFC 1052, IAB Recommendations for the Development of Internet Network Management Standards [1], the Internet Activities Board has directed the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) to create two new working groups in the area of network management.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "One group was charged with the further specification and definition of elements to be included in the Management Information Base (MIB).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The other was charged with defining the modifications to the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) to accommodate the short-term needs of the network vendor and operations communities, and to align with the output of the MIB working group.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The MIB working group produced two memos, one which defines a Structure for Management Information (SMI) [2] for use by the managed objects contained in the MIB.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A second memo [3] defines the list of managed objects.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The output of the SNMP Extensions working group is this memo, which incorporates changes to the initial SNMP definition [7] required to attain alignment with the output of the MIB working group.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The changes should be minimal in order to be consistent with the IAB's directive that the working groups be \"extremely sensitive to the need to keep the SNMP simple.\" Although considerable care and debate has gone into the changes to the SNMP which are reflected in this memo, the resulting protocol is not backwardly-compatible with its predecessor, the Simple Gateway Monitoring Protocol (SGMP) [8].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Although the syntax of the protocol has been altered, the original philosophy, design decisions, and architecture remain intact.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In order to avoid confusion, new UDP ports have been allocated for use by the protocol described in this memo.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elemen:
{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.1. Common Constructs": [
        {
            "Original": "Before introducing the six PDU types of the protocol, it is appropriate to consider some of the ASN.1 constructs used frequently: \\-- request/response information RequestID ::= INTEGER ErrorStatus ::= INTEGER { noError(0), tooBig(1), noSuchName(2), badValue(3), readOnly(4) genErr(5) } ErrorIndex ::= INTEGER \\-- variable bindings VarBind ::= SEQUENCE { name ObjectName, value ObjectSyntax } VarBindList ::= SEQUENCE OF VarBind RequestIDs are used to distinguish among outstanding requests.",
            "Adjusted": "Before introducing the six PDU types of the protocol, it is appropriate to consider some of the ASN.1 constructs used frequently: request/response information includes RequestID as INTEGER, ErrorStatus as INTEGER with values noError(0), tooBig(1), noSuchName(2), badValue(3), readOnly(4), genErr(5), and ErrorIndex as INTEGER. Variable bindings include VarBind as SEQUENCE of name ObjectName and value ObjectSyntax, and VarBindList as SEQUENCE OF VarBind. RequestIDs are used to distinguish among outstanding requests."
        },
        {
            "Original": "By use of the RequestID, an SNMP application entity can correlate incoming responses with outstanding requests.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In cases where an unreliable datagram service is being used, the RequestID also provides a simple means of identifying messages duplicated by the network.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A non-zero instance of ErrorStatus is used to indicate that an exception occurred while processing a request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In these cases, ErrorIndex may provide additional information by indicating which variable in a list caused the exception.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The term variable refers to an instance of a managed object.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A variable binding, or VarBind, refers to the pairing of the name of a variable to the variable's value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A VarBindList is a simple list of variable names and corresponding values.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some PDUs are concerned only with the name of a variable and not its value (e.g., the GetRequest-PDU).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this case, the value portion of the binding is ignored by the protocol entity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, the value portion must still have valid ASN.1 syntax and encoding.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is recommended that the ASN.1 value NULL be used for the value portion of such bindings.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

4. Protocol Specification:
{
    "4. Protocol Specification": [
        {
            "Original": "The network management protocol is an application protocol by which the variables of an agent's MIB may be inspected or altered.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Communication among protocol entities is accomplished by the exchange of messages, each of which is entirely and independently represented within a single UDP datagram using the basic encoding rules of ASN.1 (as discussed inSection 3.2.2).",
            "Adjusted": "Communication among protocol entities is accomplished by the exchange of messages, each of which is entirely and independently represented within a single UDP datagram using the basic encoding rules of ASN.1 (as discussed in Section 3.2.2)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A message consists of a version identifier, an SNMP community name, and a protocol data unit (PDU).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A protocol entity receives messages at UDP port 161 on the host with which it is associated for all messages except for those which report traps (i.e., all messages except those which contain the Trap-PDU).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Messages which report traps should be received on UDP port 162 for further processing.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "An implementation of this protocol need not accept messages whose length exceeds 484 octets.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, it is recommended that implementations support larger datagrams whenever feasible.",
            "Adjusted": "However, it is recommended that implementations support larger datagrams whenever feasible."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is mandatory that all implementations of the SNMP support the five PDUs: GetRequest-PDU, GetNextRequest-PDU, GetResponse-PDU, SetRequest-PDU, and Trap-PDU.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "RFC1157-SNMP DEFINITIONS ::= BEGIN IMPORTS ObjectName, ObjectSyntax, NetworkAddress, IpAddress, TimeTicks FROM RFC1155-SMI; \\-- top-level message Message ::= SEQUENCE { version -- version-1 for this RFC INTEGER { version-1(0) }, community -- community name OCTET STRING, data -- e.g., PDUs if trivial ANY -- authentication is being used } \\-- protocol data units PDUs ::= CHOICE { get-request GetRequest-PDU, get-next-request GetNextRequest-PDU, get-response GetResponse-PDU, set-request SetRequest-PDU, trap Trap-PDU } \\-- the individual PDUs and commonly used \\-- data types will be defined later END",
            "Adjusted": "The RFC1157-SNMP definitions begin with imports from RFC1155-SMI including ObjectName, ObjectSyntax, NetworkAddress, IpAddress, and TimeTicks. The top-level message structure consists of a version identifier (version-1 for this RFC), a community name as an OCTET STRING, and data which may contain PDUs if trivial authentication is used. The protocol data units (PDUs) include choices for get-request, get-next-request, get-response, set-request, and trap PDUs. The individual PDUs and commonly used data types will be defined later."
        }
    ]
}

4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elemen:
{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU -> 4.1.6.3. The linkDown Trap": [
        {
            "Original": "A linkDown(2) trap signifies that the sending protocol entity recognizes a failure in one of the communication links represented in the agent's configuration.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Trap-PDU of type linkDown contains as the first element of its variable-bindings, the name and value of the ifIndex instance for the affected interface.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU -> 4.1.6.4. The linkUp Trap": [
        {
            "Original": "A linkUp(3) trap signifies that the sending protocol entity recognizes that one of the communication links represented in the agent's configuration has come up.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Trap-PDU of type linkUp contains as the first element of its variable-bindings, the name and value of the ifIndex instance for the affected interface.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU": [
        {
            "Original": "The form of the Trap-PDU is: Trap-PDU ::= [4] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { enterprise -- type of object generating \\-- trap, see sysObjectID in [5] OBJECT IDENTIFIER, agent-addr -- address of object generating NetworkAddress, -- trap generic-trap -- generic trap type INTEGER { coldStart(0), warmStart(1), linkDown(2), linkUp(3), authenticationFailure(4), egpNeighborLoss(5), enterpriseSpecific(6) }, specific-trap -- specific code, present even INTEGER, -- if generic-trap is not \\-- enterpriseSpecific time-stamp -- time elapsed between the last TimeTicks, -- (re)initialization of the network \\-- entity and the generation of the trap variable-bindings -- \"interesting\" information VarBindList } The Trap-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of the SNMP application entity.",
            "Adjusted": "The form of the Trap-PDU is: Trap-PDU ::= [4] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { enterprise OBJECT IDENTIFIER, agent-addr NetworkAddress, generic-trap INTEGER, specific-trap INTEGER, time-stamp TimeTicks, variable-bindings VarBindList } The Trap-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of the SNMP application entity."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The means by which an SNMP application entity selects the destination addresses of the SNMP application entities is implementation-specific.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of the Trap-PDU, the receiving protocol entity presents its contents to its SNMP application entity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The significance of the variable-bindings component of the Trap-PDU is implementation-specific.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Interpretations of the value of the generic-trap field are:",
            "Adjusted": "Interpretations of the value of the generic-trap field are implementation-specific."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU -> 4.1.6.7. The enterpriseSpecific Trap": [
        {
            "Original": "A enterpriseSpecific(6) trap signifies that the sending protocol entity recognizes that some enterprise-specific event has occurred.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The specific-trap field identifies the particular trap which occurred.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU -> 4.1.6.6. The egpNeighborLoss Trap": [
        {
            "Original": "An egpNeighborLoss(5) trap signifies that an EGP neighbor for whom the sending protocol entity was an EGP peer has been marked down and the peer relationship no longer obtains.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Trap-PDU of type egpNeighborLoss contains as the first element of its variable-bindings, the name and value of the egpNeighAddr instance for the affected neighbor.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.2. The GetRequest-PDU": [
        {
            "Original": "The form of the GetRequest-PDU is: GetRequest-PDU ::= [0] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { request-id RequestID, error-status -- always 0 ErrorStatus, error-index -- always 0 ErrorIndex, variable-bindings VarBindList } The GetRequest-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of its SNMP application entity.",
            "Adjusted": "The form of the GetRequest-PDU is: GetRequest-PDU ::= [0] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { request-id RequestID, error-status ErrorStatus, error-index ErrorIndex, variable-bindings VarBindList }. The GetRequest-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of its SNMP application entity."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of the GetRequest-PDU, the receiving protocol entity responds according to any applicable rule in the list below: (1) If, for any object named in the variable-bindings field, the object's name does not exactly match the name of some object available for get operations in the relevant MIB view, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is noSuchName, and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name component in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(2) If, for any object named in the variable-bindings field, the object is an aggregate type (as defined in the SMI), then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is noSuchName, and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name component in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(3) If the size of the GetResponse-PDU generated as described below would exceed a local limitation, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is tooBig, and the value of the error-index field is zero.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(4) If, for any object named in the variable-bindings field, the value of the object cannot be retrieved for reasons not covered by any of the foregoing rules, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is genErr and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name component in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If none of the foregoing rules apply, then the receiving protocol entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU such that, for each object named in the variable- bindings field of the received message, the corresponding component of the GetResponse-PDU represents the name and value of that variable.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value of the error- status field of the GetResponse- PDU is noError and the value of the error-index field is zero.",
            "Adjusted": "The value of the error-status field of the GetResponse-PDU is noError and the value of the error-index field is zero."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value of the request-id field of the GetResponse-PDU is that of the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "The value of the request-id field of the GetResponse-PDU is the same as the request-id field of the received message."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.6. The Trap-PDU -> 4.1.6.5. The authenticationFailure Trap": [
        {
            "Original": "An authenticationFailure(4) trap signifies that the sending protocol entity is the addressee of a protocol message that is not properly authenticated.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "While implementations of the SNMP must be capable of generating this trap, they must also be capable of suppressing the emission of such traps via an implementation-specific mechanism.",
            "Adjusted": "While implementations of the SNMP must be capable of generating the authenticationFailure trap, the SNMP implementations must also be capable of suppressing the emission of such traps via an implementation-specific mechanism."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.3. The GetNextRequest-PDU": [
        {
            "Original": "The form of the GetNextRequest-PDU is identical to that of the GetRequest-PDU except for the indication of the PDU type.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the ASN.1 language: GetNextRequest-PDU ::= [1] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { request-id RequestID, error-status -- always 0 ErrorStatus, error-index -- always 0 ErrorIndex, variable-bindings VarBindList } The GetNextRequest-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of its SNMP application entity.",
            "Adjusted": "The GetNextRequest-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of its SNMP application entity."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of the GetNextRequest-PDU, the receiving protocol entity responds according to any applicable rule in the list below: (1) If, for any object name in the variable-bindings field, that name does not lexicographically precede the name of some object available for get operations in the relevant MIB view, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is noSuchName, and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name component in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(2) If the size of the GetResponse-PDU generated as described below would exceed a local limitation, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is tooBig, and the value of the error-index field is zero.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(3) If, for any object named in the variable-bindings field, the value of the lexicographical successor to the named object cannot be retrieved for reasons not covered by any of the foregoing rules, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is genErr and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name component in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If none of the foregoing rules apply, then the receiving protocol entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU such that, for each name in the variable-bindings field of the received message, the corresponding component of the GetResponse-PDU represents the name and value of that object whose name is, in the lexicographical ordering of the names of all objects available for get operations in the relevant MIB view, together with the value of the name field of the given component, the immediate successor to that value.",
            "Adjusted": "If none of the foregoing rules apply, then the receiving protocol entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU such that, for each name in the variable-bindings field of the received message, the corresponding component of the GetResponse-PDU represents the name and value of that object whose name is the immediate successor to the name field value in the lexicographical ordering of all objects available for get operations in the relevant MIB view."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value of the error-status field of the GetResponse-PDU is noError and the value of the errorindex field is zero.",
            "Adjusted": "The value of the error-status field of the GetResponse-PDU is noError and the value of the error-index field is zero."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value of the request-id field of the GetResponse-PDU is that of the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "The value of the request-id field of the GetResponse-PDU is that of the received GetNextRequest-PDU message."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure": [
        {
            "Original": "This section describes the actions of a protocol entity implementing the SNMP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note, however, that it is not intended to constrain the internal architecture of any conformant implementation.",
            "Adjusted": "Note, however, that this section is not intended to constrain the internal architecture of any conformant implementation."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the text that follows, the term transport address is used.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the case of the UDP, a transport address consists of an IP address along with a UDP port.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Other transport services may be used to support the SNMP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In these cases, the definition of a transport address should be made accordingly.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The top-level actions of a protocol entity which generates a message are as follows: (1) It first constructs the appropriate PDU, e.g., the GetRequest-PDU, as an ASN.1 object.",
            "Adjusted": "The top-level actions of a protocol entity which generates a message are as follows: (1) The protocol entity first constructs the appropriate PDU, e.g., the GetRequest-PDU, as an ASN.1 object."
        },
        {
            "Original": "(2) It then passes this ASN.1 object along with a community name its source transport address and the destination transport address, to the service which implements the desired authentication scheme.",
            "Adjusted": "(2) The protocol entity then passes this ASN.1 object along with a community name, its source transport address and the destination transport address, to the service which implements the desired authentication scheme."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This authentication service returns another ASN.1 object.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(3) The protocol entity then constructs an ASN.1 Message object, using the community name and the resulting ASN.1 object.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(4) This new ASN.1 object is then serialized, using the basic encoding rules of ASN.1, and then sent using a transport service to the peer protocol entity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Similarly, the top-level actions of a protocol entity which receives a message are as follows: (1) It performs a rudimentary parse of the incoming datagram to build an ASN.1 object corresponding to an ASN.1 Message object.",
            "Adjusted": "Similarly, the top-level actions of a protocol entity which receives a message are as follows: (1) The protocol entity performs a rudimentary parse of the incoming datagram to build an ASN.1 object corresponding to an ASN.1 Message object."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the parse fails, it discards the datagram and performs no further actions.",
            "Adjusted": "If the parse fails, the protocol entity discards the datagram and performs no further actions."
        },
        {
            "Original": "(2) It then verifies the version number of the SNMP message.",
            "Adjusted": "(2) The protocol entity then verifies the version number of the SNMP message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If there is a mismatch, it discards the datagram and performs no further actions.",
            "Adjusted": "If there is a mismatch, the protocol entity discards the datagram and performs no further actions."
        },
        {
            "Original": "(3) The protocol entity then passes the community name and user data found in the ASN.1 Message object, along with the datagram's source and destination transport addresses to the service which implements the desired authentication scheme.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This entity returns another ASN.1 object, or signals an authentication failure.",
            "Adjusted": "This authentication service returns another ASN.1 object, or signals an authentication failure."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the latter case, the protocol entity notes this failure, (possibly) generates a trap, and discards the datagram and performs no further actions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(4) The protocol entity then performs a rudimentary parse on the ASN.1 object returned from the authentication service to build an ASN.1 object corresponding to an ASN.1 PDUs object.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the parse fails, it discards the datagram and performs no further actions.",
            "Adjusted": "If the parse fails, the protocol entity discards the datagram and performs no further actions."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Otherwise, using the named SNMP community, the appropriate profile is selected, and the PDU is processed accordingly.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If, as a result of this processing, a message is returned then the source transport address that the response message is sent from shall be identical to the destination transport address that the original request message was sent to.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Elements of Procedure -> 4.1.5. The SetRequest-PDU": [
        {
            "Original": "The form of the SetRequest-PDU is identical to that of the GetRequest-PDU except for the indication of the PDU type.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In the ASN.1 language: SetRequest-PDU ::= [3] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { request-id RequestID, error-status -- always 0 ErrorStatus, error-index -- always 0 ErrorIndex, variable-bindings VarBindList } The SetRequest-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of its SNMP application entity.",
            "Adjusted": "In the ASN.1 language, the SetRequest-PDU is defined as: SetRequest-PDU ::= [3] IMPLICIT SEQUENCE { request-id RequestID, error-status -- always 0 ErrorStatus, error-index -- always 0 ErrorIndex, variable-bindings VarBindList }. The SetRequest-PDU is generated by a protocol entity only at the request of its SNMP application entity."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of the SetRequest-PDU, the receiving entity responds according to any applicable rule in the list below: (1) If, for any object named in the variable-bindings field, the object is not available for set operations in the relevant MIB view, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is noSuchName, and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name component in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(2) If, for any object named in the variable-bindings field, the contents of the value field does not, according to the ASN.1 language, manifest a type, length, and value that is consistent with that required for the variable, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is badValue, and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(3) If the size of the Get Response type message generated as described below would exceed a local limitation, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is tooBig, and the value of the error-index field is zero.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "(4) If, for any object named in the variable-bindings field, the value of the named object cannot be altered for reasons not covered by any of the foregoing rules, then the receiving entity sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form, except that the value of the error-status field is genErr and the value of the error-index field is the index of said object name component in the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If none of the foregoing rules apply, then for each object named in the variable-bindings field of the received message, the corresponding value is assigned to the variable.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each variable assignment specified by the SetRequest-PDU should be effected as if simultaneously set with respect to all other assignments specified in the same message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The receiving entity then sends to the originator of the received message the GetResponse-PDU of identical form except that the value of the error-status field of the generated message is noError and the value of the error-index field is zero.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

